Diagnosis . This species (
Fig. 33
) is distinctive by the flatter pronotum, which is widest in the middle and with sides markedly arcuate. Elytra uniformly black; prosternal lobe deeply incised (
Fig. 57
); prosternal process expanded, sides rectilinear (
Fig. 57
); basal abdominal ventrite with tubercles in male and apex of last abdominal ventrite subtruncate or faintly emarginate. Aedeagus (
Fig. 76
).
